# Eight traditions on pre-human intelligent species: a primary-text dossier

**The primary-language sources of eight traditions converge on a single startling pattern: pre-human intelligent populations are described not as metaphor but as literal embodied beings — petrified, exterminated, instrumentalized, or driven underground — and the Æsir, Devas, Inca creators, and angelic hierarchies achieve their dominion through specific acts of species-subordination.** The convergence is structural rather than diffusionist: each tradition's primary texts (Ge'ez 1 Enoch, Sanskrit Purāṇas and Mahābhārata, Classical Chinese Shanhaijing, Old Irish Cath Maige Tuired, Old Norse Eddas, Avestan Yašts, colonial-era Quechua Huarochirí, classical Arabic tafsīr) record the displacement using indigenous vocabulary that resists assimilation to later monotheist categories. Three critical philological findings emerge: the famous al-Masʿūdī "28 pre-Adamic nations" passage is misattributed in modern citation (it is in *Akhbār al-Zamān*, not *Murūj al-Dhahab*); the brain-feeding motif of Zaḥḥāk has **no Avestan or Pahlavi attestation** and is purely Ferdowsīan (c. 1000 AD); and the Ethiopian Orthodox internal commentary (Andǝmta) on 1 Enoch reads the Watchers metaphorically as Sethite "holy men," not as literal angelic species. What follows is a tradition-by-tradition dossier of the located primary passages, original-language text, literal translations, edition citations, classification, confidence ratings, and explicit null results.

---

## Tradition 1: Arabic — al-Ḥinn wa-l-Binn and the pre-Adamic corpus

**Ibn Kathīr, *al-Bidāya wa-l-Nihāya*, bāb dhikr khalq al-jānn wa-qiṣṣat al-shayṭān** (Dār Hajr/Turkī ed., vol. 1, pp. 128–129; Shamela 4445) preserves the foundational passage:

> «قَالَ كَثِيرٌ مِنْ عُلَمَاءِ التَّفْسِيرِ: خُلِقَتِ الْجِنُّ قَبْلَ آدَمَ عَلَيْهِ السَّلَامُ، وَكَانَ قَبْلَهُمْ فِي الْأَرْضِ الْحِنُّ وَالْبِنُّ، فَسَلَّطَ اللَّهُ الْجِنَّ عَلَيْهِمْ فَقَتَلُوهُمْ، وَأَجْلَوْهُمْ عَنْهَا وَأَبَادُوهُمْ مِنْهَا، وَسَكَنُوهَا بَعْدَهُمْ بِسَبَبِ مَا أَحْدَثُوا.»

"Many exegetes have said: the Jinn were created before Adam; and before them on earth were al-Ḥinn and al-Binn. So God set the Jinn upon them, who killed them, drove them out, exterminated them, and dwelt there after them — on account of what they had wrought." **Ibn Kathīr supplies no isnād for the al-Ḥinn/al-Binn statement itself**, presenting it as the impersonal view of "many exegetes"; the surrounding ʿAzāzīl/Iblīs material has full isnāds to Ibn ʿAbbās via al-Suddī, al-Ḍaḥḥāk, and Ibn Isḥāq. Ibn Kathīr's own framing of the al-Suddī chain elsewhere as containing isrāʾīliyyāt («فهذا الإسناد إلى هؤلاء الصحابة مشهور في تفسير السدي ويقع فيه إسرائيليات كثيرة») classifies this material as **isrāʾīliyyāt / akhbār al-mufassirīn**, not Quranic and not marfūʿ hadith. Classification: literal physical (spatial, mortal, exterminable); confidence: high.

**Critical correction on the 28 pre-Adamic nations.** The famous catalogue is **not in *Murūj al-Dhahab*** as widely cited — it is in al-Masʿūdī's earlier compilation **Akhbār al-Zamān wa-man abādahu al-ḥidthān**, chapter «ذكر الأمم المخلوقات قبل آدم» (Dār al-Andalus, Beirut 1416/1996, p. 32; Shamela 8620). The text frames 28 nations corresponding to the lunar mansions, generated from differing mixtures of the four elements:

> «يُقَالُ إِنَّهُ كَانَتِ الْجُمْلَةُ ثَمَانِيًا وَعِشْرِينَ أُمَّةً بِإِزَاءِ الْمَنَازِلِ الْعَالِيَةِ الَّتِي يَحُلُّهَا الْقَمَرُ … وَمِنْهَا أُمَّةٌ طِوَالٌ خِفَافٌ زُرْقٌ ذَاتُ أَجْنِحَةٍ كَلَامُهُمْ فَرْقَعَةٌ، وَمِنْهَا أُمَّةٌ أَبْدَانُهُمْ كَأَبْدَانِ الْأُسْدِ وَرُؤُوسُهُمْ رُؤُوسُ الطَّيْرِ … وَمِنْهَا أُمَّةٌ لَهَا وَجْهَانِ قُدَّامَهَا وَخَلْفَهَا وَأَرْجُلٌ كَثِيرَةٌ وَكَلَامُهُمْ كَلَامُ الطَّيْرِ …»

"A nation tall, light, blue, winged, whose speech is a crackling; a nation with bodies like lions and heads like birds, with hair and long tails, speech a buzzing; a nation with two faces — one front, one back — and many legs, whose speech is the speech of birds." Further: tortoise-backed with horn, dagger-fanged with long ears, cow-tailed and white-haired, female-only forms. **Al-Masʿūdī cites no source**, framing with the impersonal *yuqāl*; the cosmological apparatus (28 = lunar mansions; humoral-elemental etiology) is Hellenistic-Hermetic. **Single-attestation confirmed**: no parallel in al-Ṭabarī, Ibn al-Athīr, or al-Yaʿqūbī. Later compilers cite only al-Masʿūdī; Ibn al-Dawādārī's *Kanz al-Durar* (Shamela 18147) reproduces a comparable chapter explicitly under his name, and adds a discrete chapter **«ذكر الحن والبن والطم والرم»** grouping al-Ḥinn, al-Binn, al-Ṭamm, and al-Rimm as four pre-Adamic categories — the most explicit single source for **Ṭamm/Rimm**. In classical lexica (*Lisān al-ʿArab*, *Tāj al-ʿArūs*) *al-ṭamm wa-l-rimm* is an idiomatic merism ("the abundant and the trifling"); its reification as species-names is a tertiary medieval development. Classification: literal physical; confidence: high for text, high for null-result on parallel attestation.

**Al-Nasnās** appears across three corpora. Al-Damīrī, *Ḥayāt al-Ḥayawān al-Kubrā* (Dār al-Kutub al-ʿIlmiyya, vol. 2, pp. 479–480) cites a transmogrification of a tribe of ʿĀd into "Nasnās, each having a single hand and a single leg from one side, leaping as a bird leaps." Al-Qazwīnī, *ʿAjāʾib al-Makhlūqāt* (Wüstenfeld ed., Göttingen 1849), locates them physically: "a nation as if a human cleft in two, found in the islands of the Sea of China." The classification oscillates between transmogrified humans, a literal physical race, and a metaphor for the rabble (*dhahaba al-nās wa-baqiya al-nasnās*). Confidence: high for al-Damīrī and al-Qazwīnī; al-Jāḥiẓ verbatim not located.

**The Iblīs / ʿAzāzīl complex** is canonical in al-Ṭabarī, *Jāmiʿ al-Bayān* on Q 2:34 (Shākir ed., ḥadīths 685–687):

> «كَانَ إِبْلِيسُ قَبْلَ أَنْ يَرْكَبَ الْمَعْصِيَةَ مِنَ الْمَلَائِكَةِ اسْمُهُ "عَزَازِيلُ"، وَكَانَ مِنْ سُكَّانِ الْأَرْضِ، وَكَانَ مِنْ أَشَدِّ الْمَلَائِكَةِ اجْتِهَادًا وَأَكْثَرِهِمْ عِلْمًا، فَذَلِكَ دَعَاهُ إِلَى الْكِبْرِ، وَكَانَ مِنْ حَيٍّ يُسَمَّوْنَ جِنًّا.»

"Iblīs, before he committed disobedience, was among the angels, his name was ʿAzāzīl; he was among the dwellers of the earth, the most strenuous of the angels in worship and the most learned — and that is what called him to pride; he was from a tribe called Jinn." Al-Thaʿlabī's *ʿArāʾis al-Majālis* (via al-Qurṭubī's quotation) adds the Syriac/Arabic doublet ("his name in Syriac was ʿAzāzīl, in Arabic al-Ḥārith") and elevates him explicitly to "chief of the angels of the lowest heaven, possessing its dominion and the dominion of the earth" — the **commander-of-the-angelic-army-against-the-corrupt-Jinn** narrative. **The popular epithet "ṭāwūs al-malāʾika" (peacock of the angels) is a null result in classical primary tafsīr/qiṣaṣ literature**: it appears in modern qiṣaṣ al-anbiyāʾ and Yezidi tradition but cannot be traced to al-Ṭabarī, al-Thaʿlabī, al-Kisāʾī, or al-Qurṭubī. The "seven-names-for-seven-heavens" angelic-rank narrative is attributed in popular literature to Ka'b al-Aḥbār lineage material transmitted via al-Ghazālī's *Mukāshafat al-Qulūb*. The Shahr b. Ḥawshab tradition (al-Ṭabarī, Ibn Kathīr) explicitly preserves the angelic-army-defeats-corrupt-Jinn-and-drives-them-to-the-islands-of-the-seas narrative.

**Atfayyish's Ibādī reading of Q 18:50** (*Himyān al-Zād ilā Dār al-Maʿād*, Zanzibar 1306–1311 H, repr. Wizārat al-Turāth al-Qawmī, Oman) argues, on the basis of *fasaqa ʿan amri rabbihi*, that Iblīs's *fisq* presupposes free will and the capacity for moral failure — which angels lack — therefore the istithnāʾ in Q 2:34 and 18:50 must be **munqaṭiʿ** (disjunctive): "but Iblīs [who was not of them, since he] was of the Jinn." This aligns with the Muʿtazila and al-Ḥasan al-Baṣrī and against the Ibn ʿAbbās/jumhūr "muttaṣil" reading. The Atfayyish primary text was not retrieved verbatim (altafsir.com and greattafsirs.com blocked by bot-detection); confidence on the Ibādī position is high, on Atfayyish's exact wording medium.

## Tradition 2: Sanskrit — pātāla, sarpa-satra, and prior manvantaras

The **seven pātālas** are described in parallel by Viṣṇu Purāṇa 2.5 and Bhāgavata Purāṇa 5.24–26, with measured cosmography (10,000 yojanas each), named populations, palace architecture, and an internally consistent **independent light-physics**: jewels on Nāga hoods provide illumination, while the sun's rays diffuse light (*prakāśa*) without heat (*na tāpāya*), and the moon shines for illumination not coolness. The Bhāgavata names the lords of the Nāga-world directly:

> ततोऽधस्तात्पाताले नागलोकपतयो वासुकिप्रमुखाः शङ्ख-कुलिक-महाशङ्ख-श्वेत-धनञ्जय-धृतराष्ट्र-शङ्खचूड-कम्बल-अश्वतर-देवदत्तादयो महाभोगिनो महामर्षा निवसन्ति। येषामु ह वै पञ्च-सप्त-दश-शत-सहस्र-शीर्षाणां फणासु विरचिता महामणयो रोचिष्णवः पातालविवरतिमिरनिकरं स्वरोचिषा विधमन्ति।

"Below that, in Pātāla, the lords of the Nāga-world headed by Vāsuki — Śaṅkha, Kulika, Mahāśaṅkha, Śveta, Dhanañjaya, Dhṛtarāṣṭra, Śaṅkhacūḍa, Kambala, Aśvatara, Devadatta and others — great enjoyers, greatly wrathful, reside. Of these, having five, seven, ten, hundred, or thousand heads, on whose hoods great gems are set, radiant, they dispel the mass of darkness in the caverns of Pātāla with their own light." (Pathak critical edition, Vadodara 1997–99; GRETIL bhp_05u.htm.) Each layer is governed: **Atala** by Bala (Maya's son), **Vitala** by Hara-Bhava with Bhavānī, **Sutala** by the asura-king Bali kept there by Vāmana, **Talātala** by the dānava-architect Maya, **Mahātala** by many-hooded Nāgas, **Rasātala** by Paṇis, Nivātakavacas, Kāleyas. The Bhāgavata's own term for these layers is **bila-svargāḥ** — "subterranean heavens" (5.24.8) — explicitly positive, paralleling the Andean ukhu pacha valuation.

The **Amṛtamanthana** narrative (Mahābhārata Ādiparva 1.15–17, BORI critical edition) discloses a paradigmatic species-displacement etiology. Vāsuki is used as the churning-rope (*netra*); the Asuras are promised co-share — *sāmānya-phala-bhoktāraḥ* — and Viṣṇu privately instructs the devas: «*tathā cāhaṃ kariṣyāmi te yathā tridaśa-dviṣaḥ / na prāpsyanty amṛtaṃ devāḥ kevalaṃ kleśa-bhāginaḥ*» — "I will so contrive that the enemies of the gods shall not obtain the amṛta — they will get only the toil." The Nāgas seize the poison emerging from the ocean while being themselves scorched. The narrative structurally enacts **triple subordination**: Vāsuki instrumentalized, Asuras deceived, Nāgas left with poison. **The devas' immortality is purchased through cosmic-political treachery against pre-deva populations.** Confidence: very high.

The **Sarpa Satra** (Ādiparva Astīka Parva, ch. 13–58 Pune CE) is unambiguous as a project of species-extermination: *sarpāṇām samucchittiḥ*. Janamejaya's snake-sacrifice burns named Nāga lineages by the hundreds (1.52 catalogues them by name); Astīka — a half-Nāga whose mother Jaratkārū is Vāsuki's sister — intervenes with the threefold *tiṣṭha tiṣṭha tiṣṭha* freezing Takṣaka in mid-air. The sacrifice is **incomplete by design**: Takṣaka spared and suspended, the Nāga lineages depleted but not annihilated. Vogel (*Indian Serpent-Lore*, 1926) and Lüders read this as historical-allegorical memory of a pogrom against an autochthonous Nāga-people, possibly the Takkas of Taxila where the sacrifice is narratively located.

**Garuḍa as anti-Naga bioweapon** is explicit in the Adi Parva. The compound **पन्नगाशनः** *pannagāśanaḥ* — "serpent-eater" — is applied to Garuḍa from birth (1.23); at 1.29.5 he is mandated *nityaṃ bhakṣayatu pannagān* — "let him eternally devour the snakes." Kaśyapa's boon to Vinatā at 1.16 specifies a son *adhikataro nāga-sahasrāt* — "stronger than the thousand Nāgas." The Sanskrit narrative literalizes interspecies cold war.

The **six previous manvantaras** (Viṣṇu Purāṇa 3.1.5–7) explicitly enumerate prior populated worlds: «*manuḥ svāyaṃbhuvaḥ pūrvaṃ tato manuḥ svārociṣaḥ / uttamas tāmasaś caiva raivataś cākṣuṣas tathā // ṣaḍ ete manavo 'tītāḥ*» — "First Manu was Svāyambhuva, then Svārociṣa, Uttama, Tāmasa, Raivata, and Cākṣuṣa likewise. These six Manus are past." Each manvantara has a **distinct deva-host** (Yāmas, Pārāvatas-Tuṣitas, Sudhāmans, Surūpas, Amitābhas, Āpyas), a different Indra (Vipaścit, Suśānti, Śibi, Vibhu, Manojava), distinct Saptarṣis, and a distinct Viṣṇu-avatāra. Classification: ambiguous-leaning-literal; the Sanskrit narrative treats prior manvantaras as historically-real prior worlds with discrete non-overlapping populations.

**Null results explicitly stated.** Specific Naga "tell-signs" (unblinking eyes, no shadow, lotus garlands) are deva-markers in Mahābhārata 3.54 (Nala-Damayantī), not Naga-specific in primary text. The lexical contrast *kāya-vyūha* (genuine bodily transformation, e.g. Surasā's expansion in Sundarakāṇḍa 5.1) vs *māyā* (illusion, e.g. Viṣṇu-Mohinī in ViP 1.9.107) is present in the texts but never doctrinally applied as a typology to Nāgas specifically.

## Tradition 3: Classical Chinese — the 人面蛇身 inventory

Shanhaijing yields a systematically catalogued inventory of **human-faced serpent-bodied beings** distributed across the eighteen juan. The most fully anatomized is **燭龍 Zhulong / 燭陰 Zhuyin** (大荒北經 / 海外北經):

> 西北海之外，赤水之北，有章尾山。有神，人面蛇身而赤，直目正乘，其瞑乃晦，其視乃明，不食不寢不息，風雨是謁。是燭九陰，是謂燭龍。

"Beyond the Northwest Sea, north of the Red Water, lies Mount Zhangwei. There is a god — human-faced, serpent-bodied, and red, with vertical eyes that stand upright. When he closes them, [the world] becomes dark; when he opens them, bright. He does not eat, sleep, or breathe; wind and rain attend him. He illumines the Nine Yin [dark regions]; he is called Zhulong." (zh.wikisource Sibu Congkan recension; Yuan Ke 袁珂, 山海經校注, Shanghai Guji 1980.) Guo Pu 郭璞 explicitly identifies Zhulong with Zhuyin: «燭，龍也。是燭九陰，因名云。» Zhulong is the clearest case in the pre-Qin canon of a **being-whose-anatomy-is-the-cosmos**: his physiological functions ARE the diurnal-seasonal-meteorological cycle (eyes-open = day, blowing = winter). The parallel typology is Babylonian Tiamat and Norse Ymir.

