The **Kunlun complex** is described in Xishan Jing as **帝之下都** — "the Lord's Lower Capital" — managed by **陸吾 Luwu** (tiger-bodied, nine-tailed, human-faced, tiger-clawed) who administers **天之九部** "the Nine Sectors of Heaven" and **帝之囿時** "the seasons of the Lord's parks." The 海內西經 parallel describes nine gates each guarded by the **開明獸 Kaiming Beast** (tiger-bodied, nine-headed, all human-faced), with the Hundred Gods residing within. Yuan Ke identifies 陸吾 and 開明獸 as the same Kunlun-guardian under different recensional names.

**Huangdi/Xuanyuan's serpentine lineage** is canonically Shanhaijing-internal and **deliberately suppressed in Shiji**: Sima Qian's 五帝本紀 explicitly demythologizes («百家言黃帝，其文不雅馴，薦紳先生難言之» — "the hundred schools speak of Huangdi, but their texts are not elegant, gentlemen find them difficult to discuss"). The State of Xuanyuan is populated by serpent-bodied beings; Huangdi's grandson Hanliu is a chimera. The serpentine Huangdi lineage is iconographically attested in Han-dynasty stone reliefs of Fuxi-Nüwa pairs — though **Fuxi and Nüwa as 人面蛇身 are NOT in the Shanhaijing main canon**; that image-tradition originates in Wang Yi's Chuci commentary, Liezi, and Han stone reliefs.

The **Gun 鯀 flood narrative** (closing pericope of 海內經) is structurally a Promethean myth: «洪水滔天。鯀竊帝之息壤以堙洪水，不待帝命。帝令祝融殺鯀於羽郊。鯀復生禹。» — "The flood-waters reached up to Heaven. **Gun stole** (*qiè* 竊) **the Self-Growing Earth** (*xī rǎng* 息壤) of the Lord to dam the flood — **he did not wait for the Lord's command** (不待帝命). The Lord commanded Zhurong to kill Gun in the wilds of Mount Yu. Gun revived/begot Yu." The three theft-topos lexemes — 竊 stole, 不待帝命 unauthorized, 令祝融殺 punished by the fire-god — are explicit. The Chuci Tianwen's skeptical question «順欲成功，帝何刑焉？» — "He intended to succeed: why did the Lord punish him?" — provides a pre-Han internal critique of the disproportionality of divine retribution against compassionate transgression. The closer parallel is to Mesopotamian Enki/Ea than to Prometheus proper, though the structural triad (theft + punishment + posthumous productivity from the figure's body) is robust.

On **絕地天通** ("severing heaven-earth communication"), the two foundational texts diverge significantly. **Shangshu Lüxing** frames it as **punishment of the Miao**: after their use of the Five-Cruel-Punishments and the slaughter of innocents, the August Lord «乃命重黎，絕地天通，罔有降格» — "commanded Chong and Li to cut off the communication between Earth and Heaven, so that there should be no descent or arrival." **Guoyu Chuyu xia** preserves the Guan Yifu 觀射父 dialogue with King Zhao of Chu where the king asks the literal question — "would people then have been able to ascend to Heaven?" — and Guan Yifu explicitly rejects it: 非此之謂也, "that is not its meaning." His exegesis frames the severance as **religious-administrative reform**: by the decline of Shaohao, the Nine Li (九黎) had caused «民神雜糅，不可方物» — "people and spirits became commingled and indistinguishable," every household becoming its own shaman-historian. Zhuanxu's command monopolizes celestial-terrestrial mediation in two specialist ministers — Chong (南正, binding spirits to heaven) and Li (火正, binding people to earth). **The severance is administrative, not literal blockage**; the two readings (punitive in Shangshu, restorative-administrative in Guoyu) are not contradictory: the Shangshu setting supplies the political occasion, the Guoyu the ritual-philosophical content.

## Tradition 4: Old Irish — Túatha Dé Danann as embodied pre-Gaelic divinities

The Old Irish corpus uniformly treats the Túatha Dé Danann as **literally physical embodied beings**. The opening passage of Cath Maige Tuired §1 (Gray, Irish Texts Society 52, 1982) parallels Lebor Gabála R¹ ¶304:

> Bátar Túathai Dé Danonn i n-indsib túascertachaib in domain, ic foglaim fesa ⁊ fithnasachta ⁊ druídechtai ⁊ amaidechtai ⁊ amainsechta, combtar fortilde for súthib cerd ngenntlichtae.

"The Túatha Dé Danann were in the northern islands of the world, learning *fis* (occult lore) and *fithnasacht* (charm-knowledge) and *druídecht* (druidry) and *amaidecht* (witchcraft) and *amainsecht* (cunning craft), until they surpassed the masters of the heathen arts." The four cities (Falias, Gorias, Findias, Murias), the four treasures (Lía Fáil, sword of Núada, spear of Lug, cauldron of the Dagda), the four teachers (Mórfesae, Esras, Uiscias, Semias), the burning of ships at the territory of Corcu Belgatan, and three days of darkness are all preserved in the Old Irish. **The burning-of-ships passage is critical**: it is the redactor's explicit rationalization of an earlier "in clouds of mist" arrival, preserved within the text as an alternative tradition — **the text itself negotiates between literal-physical and magical-aerial framings**. Among Macalister's redactions, **R¹ is closest to the 11th-century original; the Míniugud μ-stratum (witnesses μΛ in Lecan, μR in Rawl. B.512, μV in the Stowe MSS) preserves the oldest accessible textual layer**, though modern scholarship (Carey, Scowcroft) has nuanced Macalister's stemma.

**The Fomoire are not a separate species** from the TDD. Cath Maige Tuired §85 uses **fine** — technical kinship-law vocabulary — of both groups: «Rosernatai trá an cath cech láei eter **fine** Fomra ⁊ Thúatha Déa» — "the battle was drawn up each day between the **kin-group** of the Fomoire and the Túatha Dé." The Bres conception scene (CMT §§15–18) makes this concrete: Ériu daughter of Delbáeth (TDD) meets Elatha mac Delbáith (Fomoire king) on the shore, and their union produces Bres, half-Fomoire half-TDD, who later becomes king of the Túatha Dé. Lug himself is son of Cían (TDD) and Ethne daughter of Balor (Fomoire). **The two groups freely interbreed; they are conceived as biologically interfertile populations sharing kinship, not separate species.** The French Celticist tradition (Arzel Even, *Ogam* 3 n.s. 1949; Guyonvarc'h; Le Roux) reads them Dumézilianly as the powers-of-blight vs powers-of-growth functional poles of a single divine society. Confidence: very high.

The **retreat into the side** is preserved most explicitly in Altram Tige Dá Medar (Dobbs ed., Zeitschrift für celtische Philologie 18, 1930) and its Acallam na Senórach parallel:

> Ro indaig Manannán na sídhe dona feraibh-sea, ⁊ ro fhógair fledh Goibnenn doaib do dín ar aes ⁊ ar éc, ⁊ mucca Manannáin dia marbad ⁊ a tabairt i mbethaid doridhisi, ⁊ in feth fiadha co rabsat na flathai cen aicsin.

"Manannán apportioned the *síde* to these men, and proclaimed for them the Feast of Goibniu to protect them against old age and death, and the Pigs of Manannán to be killed and brought to life again, and the **féth fíada** so that the lords should be without being seen." The three institutions — féth fíada (invisibility), Fleadh Goibnenn (immortality), mucca Manannáin (inexhaustible food) — convert the TDD's defeated condition into **permanent invisible immortal coexistence**. The three framings (defeat by Milesians, strategic withdrawal on Manannán's counsel, voluntary acceptance of new ontology) are **all present and sequenced** — not alternatives. The TDD continue to exist as a parallel invisible immortal society; this is not annihilation.

The **strongest 7th-century evidence** for the indigenous Irish ontological category is Tírechán's *Collectanea* c. 26 (Book of Armagh; Bieler ed., DIAS 1979, pp. 142–145). At the well of Clébach the two daughters of King Loíguire, encountering Patrick's bishops, reckon them to be «**uiros side aut deorum terrenorum aut fantassiam**» — "**men of the síd, or earthly gods, or a phantasm**." The phrase *uiros side* directly transposes Old Irish *fir síde* into Latin because no Latin equivalent existed. The triad — **people of the síd / earthly gods (*dei terreni*) / phantasms** — is the explicit 7th-century pagan-Irish ontological taxonomy, distinguishing the TDD-class beings both from "phantasms" (mere illusions) and from the Christian "heavenly gods." **The daughters perceive Patrick AS POSSIBLY belonging to this class** — physical-locative interrogation ("where do you live, whence have you come?"). This is the strongest single-passage evidence that the pre-Christian Irish categorized the TDD as literal physical "earthly gods," not metaphors.

## Tradition 5: Old Norse — extractive cosmology and jötunn-as-knowledge-source

The Old Norse cosmogony is **extractive, not creative ex nihilo**. Gylfaginning 7–8 (Faulkes ed., Viking Society 2005, pp. 11–13) makes the verb-choice explicit:

> Þeir tóku Ymi ok fluttu í mitt Ginnungagap ok gerðu af honum jörðina, af blóði hans sæinn ok vötnin. Jörðin var ger af holdinu, en björgin af beinunum... Tóku þeir ok haus hans ok gerðu þar af himin... Þeir tóku ok heila hans ok köstuðu í loft ok gerðu af skýin.

"They **took** Ymir and conveyed him into the middle of Ginnungagap and **made of him** the earth — of his blood the sea and the waters. The earth was made from the flesh, the cliffs from the bones... They also **took** his skull and made of it the sky... They also **took** his brains and threw them into the air and made of them the clouds." The dominant verbs are *taka* "to take/seize" (governing the body as raw material) and *gera/skapa af* "to make/shape from" (governing artefacts made from pre-existing material) — there is **no verb of *ex nihilo* creation here**. Snorri's poetic source — Vafþrúðnismál 21 and Grímnismál 40–41 («Ór Ymis holdi var jörð of sköpuð...») — uses identical extractive vocabulary. The world is a fabricated artefact from a dismembered being, who is the maternal-kin of Borr's sons (Bestla, mother of Óðinn, is daughter of the jötunn Bölþorn — Gylf. 6). The cosmos is built from kin-slaughter. Classification: literal physical extraction/conquest; confidence: high.

**Bergelmir's escape in the lúðr** is more philologically ambiguous than the standard Noah-parallel reading suggests. Vafþrúðnismál 35 reads:

> Örófi vetra / áðr væri jörð of sköpuð, / þá var Bergelmir borinn; / þat ek fyrst of man, / er sá inn fróði jötunn / var **á lúðr of lagiðr**.

"Uncountable winters before the earth was shaped, then was Bergelmir born; **that I first remember**, when that wise jötunn **was laid upon a *lúðr***." The semantic range of **lúðr** in attested Old Norse covers **trumpet/horn, meal-bin/mill-trough under a quern, hollow log/mortar/cradle** — the "ark/boat" sense is **attested ONLY for the Bergelmir passage in Snorra Edda**. Cleasby-Vigfusson's primary glosses are trumpet and mill-bin; Finnur Jónsson's *Lexicon Poeticum* gives "hollow log, hollowed tree-trunk." Robert Fulk (*Review of English Studies* 40, 1989) reads the eddic verb *leggja á* "to lay upon" as suggesting an infant being laid in a cradle — a **Scyld Scefing-style infant-in-the-boat motif** rather than an adult flood-survivor. **Snorri's prose reinterpretation** adds "*ok kona hans*" (and his wife) and "*helzt þar*" (held out there), producing the Noah parallel — but this appears to be **secondary, possibly Christian-influenced**. The primordial-infancy reading is supported by "*þat ek fyrst of man*" — "that I first remember" — as a marker of deepest temporal recall: Bergelmir's *lúðr* is the omniscient jötunn's earliest memory.

The pattern that **the Æsir learn from the jötnar** is canonical across the Eddic corpus. Vafþrúðnismál is structurally a knowledge-pilgrimage: Óðinn travels to Vafþrúðnir to "*at freista orðspeki þess ins alsvinna jǫtuns*" — "to test the word-wisdom of that all-wise jötunn," seeking *fornum stǫfum* "ancient lore." Hávamál 140 is more concrete: «**Fimbulljóð níu nam ek af inum frægja syni Bölþorns**, Bestlu föður, ok ek drykk of gat ins dýra mjaðar, ausinn Óðreri» — "**Nine mighty-songs I learned from the famed son of Bölþorn**, Bestla's father, and I got a drink of the precious mead, poured from Óðrerir." **Óðinn's foundational magical knowledge is acquired from his jötunn maternal uncle.** Hávamál 104–110 narrates the theft of the mead of poetry from the jötunn Suttungr; poetic skill itself is jötunn-property. Alvíssmál enumerates jötnar as one of the eight named speech-communities of the cosmos with their own complete lexicon. The Eddic cosmos is one in which **wisdom is older than the Æsir and originally held by jötnar**.

The **Ragnarök renewal** in Völuspá 44–66 contains the critical phrase «**Sér hon upp koma öðru sinni jörð ór ægi iðjagrœna**» — "she sees coming up **a second time** the earth from the sea, ever-green" (st. 59 Konungsbók). The lexeme *öðru sinni* — "a second time" — is the strongest single textual marker of cyclicality, presupposing iteration. The recovered *gullnar töflur* "golden game-pieces" of st. 61 belong to *í árdaga* "the days of old" — continuity of identity between pre- and post-Ragnarök Æsir. **But no jötunn is named among the survivors of the renewed cosmos**: stanzas 59–64 list Æsir (Baldr, Hǫðr, Hænir, Víðarr, Váli, Móði, Magni) and humans (Líf and Lífþrasir per Vafþr. 45) only. Níðhǫggr (st. 66) appears as a residual serpent-dragon from below. **This is a null result on jötunn survival**: the Völuspá renewal-vision is Æsir-focused.

## Tradition 6: Ge'ez 1 Enoch and the Watchers — Andǝmta's metaphorical reading

The Book of the Watchers (1 Enoch 6–16) survives in Ge'ez (Knibb 1978 vol. 1, Rylands Eth. MS 23), Aramaic (4Q201, 4Q202 — Milik 1976), and Greek (Codex Panopolitanus, Syncellus — Black 1970). 1 Enoch 6:7–8 names the twenty chiefs of tens; the Aramaic 4Q201 col. iii preserves the list directly:

> ואלן שמהת רבניהון. שמיחזה הוא רבהון. ערעקף תניה לה. רמטאל תליתי לה. כוכבאל רביעי לה...

"And these are the names of their chiefs. Shemiḥazah, he was their head. Arteqoph, second. Ramṭel third. Kokabʾel fourth..." The Aramaic list ends with **Yehadiʾel** as the twentieth; the Ge'ez and Greek substitute **Sariel** — an archangel-name. **Milik 1976 p. 152 reads this substitution as late Greek redactional intervention**; for primary-source priority the Aramaic order should be preferred where it survives. The Ge'ez (Knibb pp. 65–67) reads:

> ወኮነ፡ እንዘ፡ ይበዝኁ፡ ውሉደ፡ ሰብእ፡ ኮኑ፡ ሎሙ፡ ደቂቅ፡ ኮኑ፡ ሰንያት፡ ወሠናያት። ወርእይዎን፡ መላእክት፡ ውሉደ፡ ሰማይ፡ ወፈተውዎሙ...

"It came to pass when the sons of men had multiplied, daughters were born to them, beautiful and lovely. And the angels, the sons of heaven, saw them and desired them and said one to another: 'Come, let us choose for ourselves wives from the daughters of men.'" The descent (*wäräḍu*) at Mount Hermon, the binding oath, and the technological teaching catalogue follow.

The **teaching catalogue** at 1 Enoch 8:1–3 (Knibb 75–76) is the most detailed: **ʿAzāzʾel** teaches metallurgy, weaponry, and cosmetics (swords, knives, shields, breastplates, antimony eye-paint, dye-tinctures); **Amezarak** sorcery; **Bārāqyāl** astrology; **Kokabʾel** the constellations; **ʾEzeqʾel** cloud-science; **ʾArāqʾel** earth-signs; **Säməsʾel** sun-signs; **Säriʾel** moon-courses. The Aramaic 4Q201 col. iv preserves the ʿAzazel metallurgy section directly («חרבי פרזלא ושריני נחשׁא» — "swords of iron and breastplates of bronze"), confirming the catalogue's antiquity. The astrological list is **Ge'ez and Greek primary** with only fragmentary Aramaic confirmation of the head.

**The locus classicus for the jinn-as-disembodied-hybrid hypothesis is 1 Enoch 15:8–10**, preserved only in Ge'ez and Greek (Syncellus — no Aramaic survival):

> ወይእዜ፡ ረዓይት፡ እለ፡ ተወልዱ፡ እምነ፡ መናፍስት፡ ወሥጋ፡ መናፍስተ፡ እኩያነ፡ ይሰመዩ፡ ዲበ፡ ምድር፡ ወውስተ፡ ምድር፡ ትከውን፡ መኀደሮሙ።

"And now the giants/nephilim who were born from spirits and flesh — **evil spirits (mänāfəstä ʾəkuyān)** shall they be called on the earth, and on the earth shall their dwelling be. Evil spirits have come out from their flesh, because from men they were born and from the holy ones [Watchers] their origin and first foundation is..." The text asserts as ontological fact that giants' post-mortem spirits become a permanent class of earth-bound disembodied entities. This is the **etiological charter for demonology in Second Temple Judaism**, and underlies later Christian (Tertullian, Origen) and possibly Qur'anic-jinn discussions. **Caveat**: the Aramaic is lost for this specific passage; primary witnesses are the Ge'ez plus a Greek quotation in Syncellus.

**Jubilees 10:1–14** (VanderKam CSCO 510:58–60) preserves the **Mastema 10% negotiation**, which exists only in Ge'ez:

> ወመጽአ፡ መሰቴማ፡ መኳንንተ፡ መናፍስት፡ ወይቤ፡ እግዚኦ፡ ፈጣሪ፡ አዕርፍ፡ እምብሕቲሆሙ፡ ቅድሜየ...

"And when Mastema, the leader of the spirits, came, he said: 'Lord Creator, leave some of them before me; let them listen to me and do everything that I tell them, because if none of them is left for me I shall not be able to exercise the authority of my will among humanity.'" God assigns **a tenth (ʿāśərāt)** to remain under Mastema's authority; nine-tenths descend to the place of judgement. This Ge'ez passage is the only complete textual witness (Hebrew 4Q221 frags do not cover ch. 10; no Latin or Greek coverage). Classification: literal ontological within the text's worldview; confidence: very high.

**The Ethiopian Orthodox Andǝmta commentary** (Ralph Lee, *JSP* 23.3, 2014; Cowley 1988; Mersha Alehegne 2011) is the most striking finding. **The Andǝmta — the canonical EOTC exegetical tradition codified at Gondar c. 1674 EC — reads the Watchers metaphorically as Sethite "holy men" (ቅዱሳን ሰዎች qǝddusan säwočč) who fell into "fleshly desire" (ሥጋዊ ፍላጎት), not as literal pre-human or parallel intelligent species.** Per Lee 2014: "The commentary views the fallen angels as **HOLY MEN who fell into temptation**, and reflects the strongly ascetic outlook of Ethiopian Christianity." This means **the church that canonically preserves Henok does NOT exegete it as evidence of literal non-human species.** Any literal-Watcher reading is a Western critical-academic construct, not the indigenous Ethiopian reading. There is internal tension within EOTC between liturgical-literal (hymns, Kǝbrä Nägäst) and scholastic-allegorical (Andǝmta) readings — a parallel structure to the Atfayyish vs Ṭabarī Arabic divergence.

## Tradition 7: Andean — petrified giants, Huarochirí's ñawpa pacha, and the positive Ukhu Pacha

The colonial Andean corpus presents the most aggressively filtered material — every source carries a "Four-Layer Catholic Filter" — and yet the indigenous substrate is recoverable. **Betanzos, *Suma y narración de los Incas* (1551), Part 1 Chapter 1** (Martín Rubio ed., Cuzco editions 1999/2004; ms. Fundación Bartolomé March):

> En los tiempos antiguos dicen ser la tierra e provincias de Pirú oscura y que en ella no había lumbre ni día... salió de una laguna que es e[n] esta tierra del Perú en la provincia que dicen de Colla suyo un señor que llamaron Contiti Viracocha... fuese de allí a un sitio... donde hoy día es un pueblo que llaman Tiaguanaco... Y este Contiti Viracocha dicen haber salido otra vez antes de aquella... aquella gente primera y a su señor en castigo del enojo que la hicieron hízole que se tornasen piedra.

"In ancient times they say the land of Peru was dark, without light or day... there came out of a lake in the province of Collasuyo a lord called Contiti Viracocha... he went to a site today called Tiaguanaco... And this Contiti Viracocha had come out another time previously... that first people and their lord, in punishment for the anger they caused him, he caused to turn to stone." Named locations of petrified giants: **Tiaguanaco (Tiwanaku)** as primary locus, **Cacha** (with empirically observable burnt mountain that Betanzos himself reports having seen — "yo he visto el cerro quemado"), **Urcos**. The petrification motif maps onto genuine Andean huaca-theology (huacas ARE stones/petrified ancestors; Tiwanaku megaliths are archaeologically present).

**Sarmiento de Gamboa, *Historia de los Incas* (1572), Caps. 6–7** (Bauer & Smith ed., Texas 2007) adds the explicit Quechua flood-term and the giant-pre-creation:

> Y después de criado el mundo formó un género de gigantes disformes en grandeza... y vivían en escuridad... traspasaron el precepto de Viracocha Pachayachachi, por lo cual, cayendo en su indignación, los confundió y maldijo... les envió un diluvio general, al cual ellos llaman **uñu pachacuti**, que quiere decir 'agua que trastornó la tierra'. Y dicen que llovió sesenta días y sesenta noches... sólo quedaron algunas señales de los que se convirtieron en piedras... en los edificios de **Pucara**, que es sesenta leguas del Cuzco.

"After creating the world he formed a kind of giants of monstrous size... and they lived in darkness... they transgressed the precept of Viracocha Pachayachachi, and falling under his indignation, he confounded and cursed them... he sent them a general flood, which they call **uñu pachacuti**, meaning 'water that overturned the earth.' And they say it rained **sixty days and sixty nights**... only traces remained of those who turned to stones... in the buildings of **Pucará**, sixty leagues from Cuzco." **The 60-day flood and the Pucará location are Sarmiento's, not Betanzos's** — a divergence reflecting different informants (Betanzos via Yupanqui-Atahualpa panaca through his wife Cuxirimay Ocllo; Sarmiento via the 42-informant Toledan project). Sarmiento's Catholic-overlay vocabulary is markedly heavier ("soberbia y codicia" — pride and greed; "transgredieron el precepto") and Genesis-derived; his prologue states demons "introdújoles muchas ilusiones... haciéndoles entender que él los había creado al principio, y que después por sus maldades y pecados los había destruido con diluvio" — the explicit demonological-deception thesis.

**The Huarochirí Manuscript** (BNE Madrid 3169; Taylor 1987/1999/2008 IFEA; Salomon & Urioste 1991) provides the thinnest Catholic filter and is the only substantial Quechua-language source. Its opening preserves indigenous mnemonic-historical legitimacy explicitly:

> Runa yn.o ñiscap Machoncuna ñaupa pacha quillcacta yachanman carca chayca hinantin causascancunapas manam canancamapas chincaycuc hinacho canman.

"If the ancestors of the people called Indians had known writing in **ancient times (ñawpa pacha)**, then all the things they have lived through would not have been disappearing this way up to now." Chapter 1 introduces the **earliest era**:

> Ancha ñaupa pachaqa huc huaca ñiscas yanañamca tutañamca sutioc carcan / cay huacacunactaca quipanpi huc huaca huallallo caruincho sutioc atircan.

"In very ancient times there was a huaca called Yanañamca Tutañamca. These huacas were later defeated/overcome by another huaca called Huallallo Carhuincho." Once Huallallo defeated them, "he ordered that humans should bear only two children: one to give to him [to eat], the other to be raised. People who died came back to life on the fifth day (*pichqa punchawmanta*), and the sown maize ripened on the fifth day." Cuni Raya Viracocha "in ancient times used to wander about in the form of a beggar (*wakcha*)." The **Quechua vocabulary for "pre-human" without Spanish loanwords** is extensive and stable: **ñawpa pacha** (ancient time/world), **ancha ñawpa pacha** (very ancient time), **machu/machuncuna** (ancestors), **ñawpa runa** (ancient people), **ñawpa machu** (ancient ancestor), **ñawpaq** (the previous ones), **pachakuti** (world-turning/era-change), **kay pacha vs ñawpa pacha** (present world vs prior world). The huacas in ñawpa pacha are described as **embodied, ambulatory, child-devouring, shape-shifting, fire-vs-water-combatant beings** — literal physical, not metaphorical.

**Ukhu Pacha as positive origin-realm** is preserved indirectly in three principal witnesses. Cristóbal de Molina, *Relación de las fábulas y ritos de los incas* (c. 1575; Urbano & Duviols 1989):

> [El Hacedor]... les mandó pasasen debajo de la tierra cada nación por sí. Y así, de allí cada nación salió de los lugares que les fue mandado, unos de cuevas, otros de cerros, otros de fuentes, otros de lagunas, otros de pies de árboles.

"He commanded that they pass **under the earth**, each nation by itself. And from there each nation came out from the places assigned them, some from caves, others from hills, others from springs, others from lakes, others from the foot of trees." This is the **paqarina theology** — the bedrock of Andean ethnogenesis — in which ukhu pacha is the womb-route of human emergence, NOT a hell. **The Catholic translation of "infierno" as "ukhu pacha" in the Doctrina Cristiana of the Third Council (1583–84) is itself the demonization**; the positive pre-translation meaning is recoverable.

**Pachacuti Yamqui Salcamaygua, *Relación de antigüedades* (c. 1613)** (Duviols & Itier eds., IFEA/CBC Cuzco 1993) preserves the amaru-emergence:

> En este tiempo dizen que llegó la nueua como en el Cuzco ubo un milagro que como un **yauirca o amaro** abía salido del serro de Pachatusan... y con orejas y colmillos y barbas (por causa deste amaro puso por nombre a su hijo Amaro Yupanqui).

"There was a miracle in Cuzco: a **yawirka or amaru** had come out from Mount Pachatusan... with ears and fangs and beard (because of this amaru, [Pachacuti] gave his son the name Amaru Yupanqui)." **A Christianized indigenous noble naming his eldest legitimate heir "Amaru" is decisive evidence that the amaru/yawirka was a positive symbol of dynastic potency, subterranean wisdom, and chthonic-celestial connection — not a satanic serpent.** The Coricancha-diagram drawn by Pachacuti Yamqui himself includes two amarus as cosmic axes (anan/urin), not as devils.

**Guaman Poma's five-ages scheme** (Nueva Corónica, kb.dk facsimile pp. 48–51) preserves Quechua era-names: **Wari Wira Qucha Runa → Wari Runa → Purun Runa → Awqa Runa → Inka Runa**, with the flood-term **unu yaku pachakuti** parallel to Sarmiento's. The amaru appears as honorific in Inca captain-names (Topa Amaru) and the genuine Quechua theonyms **Tiqsi Wira Qucha, Qaylla Wira Qucha, Pacha Kamaq, Runa Ruraq** are retained in the prayer-formula «Maypim kanki, maypim kanki, yaya?» — "Where are you, where are you, my father?" The Catholic overlay is heaviest here (descent from Noah's ark, 830-year duration), but the indigenous five-fold structure is preserved.

## Tradition 8: Avestan/Pahlavi — Bundahišn cosmogenesis and the Zaḥḥāk null result

The Bundahišn's creation sequence (Anklesaria 1956; Pakzad 2005) proceeds through **sky → water → earth → plants → animals (primal bull *gāw ī ēw-dād*) → Gayōmard (proto-human) → Mashye & Mashyāne (first sexed human pair)**:

> ō Ohrmazd dām ī gētīg: nazdist asmān; dudīgar āb; sidīgar zamīg; čahārom urwar; panǰom gōspand; šašom mardōm.

"Of Ohrmazd's gētīg creatures: first the sky; second water; third earth; fourth plants; fifth cattle; sixth man." The **Primal Bull is intelligent** — at Bd 4.2 its soul (Gōšurun) speaks aloud "as much as a thousand men crying together," lamenting destruction and asking «kē-š dāštārīh ī dāmān az tō hišt ēstēd?» — "who will guard the creatures you have abandoned?" **Gayōmard is ambiguous**: morphologically humanoid (white, brilliant, eyes turned upward to the great one), functionally a typological seed-prototype parallel to the Primal Bull for the animal kingdom. From his purified seed Mashye and Mashyāne grow as a single rhubarb-stalk before separating into the first human pair.

The **khrafstras** (Av. *xrafstra-*; Pahl. *xrafstr*) — noxious creatures — are **separate counter-creations of Ahriman**, NOT corrupted versions of Ohrmazd's creatures. Bd 3.15: «*u-š xrafstr pad zamīg pargand... ēdōn kū nōk-ēw-iz az suzan pad zamīg az xrafstr abē nē mānd*» — "he scattered noxious creatures over the earth... so that not even a needle's point of the earth remained free of khrafstras." The Pahlavi verbs *dād* "created," *pargand* "scattered," *frāz brēhēnīd* "fashioned forth" are creation-language, not corruption-language. Each Ohrmazdic species has its opposing khrafstra (dog vs wolf, hedgehog vs ants). Vendidad Fargard 1 enumerates **sixteen lands** each with a counter-creation by Angra Mainyu: Airyana Vaēǰah with **the red serpent** (*aži raoiδita*) and Daēva-made winter, Sughdha with locusts, Mouru with plunder and heresy, Vaēkərəta with the Pairikā Xnąϑaitī, Hyrcania with sodomy, Arachosia with corpse-burial, Caxra with corpse-cooking, etc. Some counters are literal physical afflictions (winter, locusts, ants), others moral/metaphorical (heresy, pride, doubt) — a mixed classification.

**Azhi Dahāka** in the **oldest Avestan stratum** (Yašt 5 Ābān Yašt 29–35; Yašt 9; Yašt 14; Yašt 15 Rām Yašt 19–25; Yašt 17; Yašt 19 Zamyād Yašt; Yasna 9 Hōm Yašt; Vendidad 1) is consistently a **non-human three-headed serpent-demon**: *aži-* "serpent/dragon," *druǰ* "demon, lie-being," **ϑrizafanəm ϑrikamərəδəm xšvaš-ašīm hazaŋrā-yaoxštīm** — "three-jawed, three-headed, six-eyed, of a thousand skills." He sacrifices to yazatas (Anāhitā at Bawri = Babylon, Vayu, Aṣ̌i), prays «*yat bā azəm nišā́δayeni hapta karšvairīš yāiš būmīš mašyō-šaite*» — "that I may make all the seven regions of the earth empty of men!" Each yazata refuses. Θraētaona (Pahl. Frēdōn) slays him; in Pahlavi Bundahišn 29.9, however, Frēdōn was "able to capture Dahāg but not to kill him, and afterwards bound him on Mount Damāwand" until end-times. The lineage at Bd 31.6 makes him **descendant of human Mashye on the patrilineal side, but his mother is Wadag** — an ambiguating Pahlavi-era move.

**The most critical null result of the entire dossier**: the brain-feeding motif of Zaḥḥāk has **no Avestan or Pahlavi attestation**. Across the entire Avestan corpus (Yašts 5, 9, 14, 15, 17, 19; Yasna 9; Vendīdād 1) and the complete Pahlavi corpus (Bundahišn, Dēnkard, Mēnōg ī Khrad, Zand ī Wahman Yasn, Pahlavi Rivāyat), there is **NO mention** of: snakes growing permanently from Dahāka's shoulders, human brains (*maγz*) being fed to them, daily sacrifice of two men, the cooks Armāyel/Karmāyel, or the blacksmith Kāwa rebellion. The closest pre-Ferdowsīan adjacency is the Dēnkard 9 / Bd 29.9 detail that *xrafstrān* (vermin — snakes, insects) emerge from Dahāg's **wounds** when Frēdōn strikes him on shoulder, heart, and skull with the ox-headed mace — and Ohrmazd commands him not to kill Dahāg lest the world become infested with these creatures. **The shoulder-snakes-with-brain-feeding is a Ferdowsīan innovation (c. 977–1010 AD) in the *Šāhnāma*'s Żaḥḥāk-e Mārdōš cycle, with no demonstrable Sasanian-era textual antecedent.** Confidence on the null result: high. This is a textbook case of how a late literary motif gets retrojected into "ancient Zoroastrian tradition" in modern sources.

